<subSubSection id="1E4D4F6975E85F01409B3A9862053AA5" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph id="6B791F96188ED63229595C95CA00A44A" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D46784FB05FB25302A2828586368C331" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This East African species is commonly grown as an ornamental vine and easily escapes from cultivation. It is widely naturalised in warm-temperate and subtropical areas across the world to such an extent that it is often considered to be an environmental weed. It was recently reported for the first time in the Canary Islands from several localities in La Palma, where it is naturalised now (
<bibRefCitation id="A5783D54FC80EFBB35BA6342CC96FB79" author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509398" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2018. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 2. Collectanea Botanica 37" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species - Part 2" volume="37" year="2018">Otto and Verloove 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3171F01C40A4326BC949EE594A9A772B" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In January 2017, it was observed for the first time in Tenerife, in a ravine in an urban environment in Tejina (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AC46E187893104B7F7C202ED560F5E6D" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F6510171" captionText="Figure 10. Thunbergia alata, San Cristobal de La Laguna (Tejina), January 2017." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494351" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
